The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 BRIEFS

 Calcutta, Nov. 16: About 2,000 trucks are waiting at the Petrapole border, unable to cross over to Bangladesh because movement of traffic in the strife-torn country has been very slow.

 Onion worth Rs 10 lakh have rotted at the North 24-Parganas border, 70 km from Calcutta, said a truck owners association. Food, textiles, chemicals, steel and minerals travel to Bangladesh through Petrapole.

 New Delhi: The Supreme Court has asked Bengal to reconsider its decision to discontinue with a scheme for the disabled conceived and initially funded by the Centre. The state had expressed its inability to continue with the 1998 project, rendering many jobless. The court said the their services should be continued.

 Calcutta: The government has set up a panel to sound out students, teachers and guardians on beginning school sessions from January instead of March.

 Calcutta: Trinamul leader Partha Chatterjee has described the Assemblys industry standing committee as a stooge of the state government. The panel, headed by a Congress MLA, had toured Tata Motors Pune plant and praised its development work there.




